ly giving rise to contemporary ideas. The collection is essential reading for scholars interested in the history of intelligence, intellectual disability and related concepts, as well as in disability history generally.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aDevelopmental disabilitiesxPsychological aspects. 0aIntellectxHistory. 0aIntellectual disability in literature. 0aIntellectual disabilityxHistory. 0aIntellectual disabilityxPhilosophy. 0aIntellectual disabilityxReligious aspects. 0aIntellectual disabilityxSocial aspects. 7aHISTORY / Social History.2bisacsh  aBritish history.  aConceptual history.  aEuropean history.  aFolly.  aHistory of ideas.  aIdiocy.  aIntellectual disability history.  aLearning disability history.  aLiterary history.1 aBranch, Katie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDillig, Janina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFleat, Clemma, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGabbard, D. Christoper, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoodey, C. F., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGoodey, C.F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoodey,, C.F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrove, Nicola, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJarrett, Simon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLumley Smith, Tim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcDonagh, Patrick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcDonagh, Patrick, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMeader, Robin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/v